TY  - JOUR
T1  - Gender Differences in Managers' Developmental Job Experiences
AU  - Ohlott, Patricia J.
AU  - Ruderman, Marian N.
AU  - McCauley, Cynthia D.
Y1  - 1994/02/01
PY  - 1994
DA  - 1994/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256769
DO  - 10.5465/256769
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 46
EP  - 67
VL  - 37
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - It has been suggested that one reason so few women have been promoted to senior management positions is that during their careers they experience fewer developmental job opportunities than men. To test this idea, we surveyed male and female managers about developmental components in their current jobs. Results suggest that men experience some greater task-related developmental challenges, but women experience greater developmental challenges stemming from obstacles they face in their jobs.
AB  - It has been suggested that one reason so few women have been promoted to senior management positions is that during their careers they experience fewer developmental job opportunities than men. To test this idea, we surveyed male and female managers about developmental components in their current jobs. Results suggest that men experience some greater task-related developmental challenges, but women experience greater developmental challenges stemming from obstacles they face in their jobs.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/256769
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/256769
Y2  - 2026/04/24
